{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee456e14-85f6-4ab2-90e1-30f621279065","content":"There's no pipeline file here, so here's a general guide:\n\n### Key changes\n\n**1. Replace `VSTest@3` with `DotNetCoreCLI@2` (or a plain `dotnet test` script)**\n\nMicrosoft.Testing.Platform runs via `dotnet test`, not `vstest.console`. Replace:\n\n```yaml\n# ❌ Old – VSTest runner\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**/*Tests.dll'\n    resultsFolder: $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```yaml\n# ✅ New – Microsoft.Testing.Platform via dotnet test\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration Release\n      --logger \"trx;LogFileName=results.trx\"\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\n**2. Publish TRX results** (VSTest@3 did this automatically):\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish test results'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n```\n\n**3. Publish code coverage**:\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish code coverage'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n> If you use the built-in Microsoft \"Code Coverage\" collector, add `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=Cobertura\"` so the output is in Cobertura XML (required by `PublishCodeCoverageResults@2`).\n\n### Checklist\n\n| Item | Action |\n|---|---|\n| NuGet packages | Ensure test projects reference `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` (and `MSTest.TestFramework` ≥ 3.x) |\n| TRX logger | `--logger trx` is built-in; no extra package needed |\n| Code coverage format | Use `Format=Cobertura` in `--collect` so the publish task can read it |\n| `condition: always()` | Ensures results/coverage publish even on test failure |\n| Parallel runs | Add `-- RunConfiguration.MaxCpuCount=0` if you want parallelism |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80cd64aa-946f-43b6-bbc2-4f5dc8ed130c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is a general knowledge question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in an Azure DevOps CI pipeline. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":697,"requestId":"9846:336ED9:166162:1D7A97:69FFD801"},"id":"2e07b3a0-e70d-4d24-927f-939ce6fa3936","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:57:51.153Z","parentId":"9e178ea6-9efc-4047-bef5-6c02b8157796"}
